    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:645743eb-2aba-4882-b39e-fc104682c93d",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 32-year-old woman who presents to the outpatient psychiatry clinic for a scheduled follow-up. She is of mixed Latinx heritage, with dark curly hair pulled back loosely and tired, expressive eyes that shift between intense engagement and distant distraction. At today's visit, she appears slightly disheveled — her clothes mismatched and her speech mildly pressured — suggesting she may be entering a hypomanic phase after several weeks of relative stability.\n\n{patientName} works as a freelance graphic designer, a career she finds both liberating and overwhelming. She thrives during high-energy creative sprints but struggles to maintain deadlines and client relationships during depressive episodes. She lives in a one-bedroom apartment in a mid-sized city and describes her social world as \"a handful of very patient close friends.\" She has a long-term on-and-off romantic relationship that has been strained by her mood instability, and she attends bi-weekly group therapy for people with mood disorders.\n\nOutside of work, {patientName} enjoys painting, listening to indie and jazz music, and taking long urban walks with her rescue dog, Mochi. During manic episodes, she tends to start multiple ambitious projects at once — recently she began remodeling her apartment herself, signed up for two online courses, and attempted to launch a new business, all within a single week. During depressive phases, she can barely leave bed and loses interest in all activities she normally loves.\n\n{patientName} reports that her current sleep has been reduced to about 4 hours per night for the past five days, she feels \"wired but exhausted,\" and she has been spending impulsively — notably purchasing over $800 in art supplies she does not need. Her appetite is decreased and her concentration is scattered. She denies suicidal ideation at this time but endorses a previous episode where she had passive thoughts of self-harm during a severe depressive episode two years ago.\n\nHer support network includes her mother (who has the same diagnosis) and one close friend who accompanies her to some appointments. {patientName} expresses ambivalence about her medications, stating that she sometimes misses them because she \"likes the energy\" of her hypomanic states, even though she intellectually understands the risks. She is insightful, articulate, and motivated for recovery when in a stable mood."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
